        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity: The CO(3-2) line luminosity of ULASJ1234+0907 is predicted to be 6.05x10^10 K km/s pc^2. This corresponds to the most conservative estimate of the line luminosity in this source utilising the lowest LFIR consistent with our Herschel observations of the source as well as the most conservative predictions for the form of the CO excitation ladder (see Scientific Justification). The line luminosity translates to a line intensity of 1.9 Jy km/s and the expected linewidth is 600 km/s. Our aim is to detect this line at high significance to enable a robust estimate of the molecular gas mass through the CO line luminosity. We also aim to obtain an estimate of the line profile over 4x150 km/s channels in order to allow a measurement of the CO linewidth and therefore the dynamical mass.

We assume a linewidth of 600 km/s for CO(3-2) which is typical of both starburst galaxies and quasar hosts in which CO has been detected at high redshifts. The above line intensity therefore translates to a peak flux density of 3.2mJy. Our proposed sensitivity of 0.3mJy is designed to detect this peak flux at &gt;10-sigma. As this is a detection experiment, we will make use of the most compact configuration available corresponding to angular scales of 3.8". The CO emission will be spatially unresolved and these observations can effectively make use of the poorest weather conditions to easily detect the molecular gas in this bright high redshift quasar.   

The proposed observations will also provide a useful upper limit on the dust continuum emission at 3mm and therefore the cool dust mass. At our proposed sensitivity, we do not expect to detect this cool dust emission at high significance. From our best-fit Herschel SED, the 3mm continuum flux density is expected to be ~0.04mJy. The proposed sensitivity has been chosen to provide a high significance detection of CO(3-2) line in this quasar in a total integration time of &lt;1hr but will nevertheless provide useful upper limits on the dust continuum.

Correlator setup: We will observe the target using the TDM mode corresponding to 128 channels over a bandwidth of 2000MHz (1875MHz effective) per spectral window. This is the largest bandwidth available and is used to account for any offsets between CO and our measured Halpha redshifts. The velocity resolution will be ~100 km/s. The line is contained in a single baseband and the remaining three basebands covering a total bandwidth of 5.6GHz, are positioned so as to enable a reliable continuum measurement. Assuming a linewidth of 600 km/s, we will spectrally resolve the line into 6x100 km/s channels which can be binned up to 4x150 km/s channels if necessary. The spectral resolution in the TDM mode is still sufficient to allow a measurement of the line profile even if the linewidth is narrower than 600 km/s. With our proposed sensitivity of 0.3mJy or 0.18Jy km/s over 4x150 km/s channels, we will easily detect at &gt;10-sigma the CO(3-2) line of intensity 1.9 Jy km/s. 

Using the ALMA Sensitivity Calculator we estimate that this sensitivity of 0.3mJy can be reached over a bandwidth of 150 km/s using 34 12m antennae in an integration time of just under 19 mins. This calculation assumes 5.186mm water vapour column density (7th octile). Including overheads and calibration, the observations can be completed in just over 47 mins. 
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
