    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We aim to detect molecular gas (C0(3-2)) in the dustiest Type 1 quasar known: ULASJ1234+0907 at z=2.5. This quasar is among the most bolometrically luminous quasars known with an intrinsic AGN luminosity that rivals the most luminous quasars in the Universe e.g. Cloverleaf and APM08279. ULASJ1234+0907 is X-ray luminous (L2-10keV=1.3e45 erg/s) but with NH=9e21/cm^2 rendering it invisible in the deepest optical surveys. Herschel observations demonstrate that the quasar host is among the most far infrared luminous galaxies identified at any redshift (log10(LIR)=13.90) with significant amounts of cool dust being heated by both the AGN and a powerful starburst. Through sub-arcsecond deep optical and infrared imaging we have established that ULASJ1234+0907 is highly unlikely to be lensed. The proposed ALMA detection experiment would enable us to determine what is fuelling both the enormous star formation and accretion onto the black-hole in this uniquely bright quasar. A very small investment of ALMA time in the current cycle would significantly advance our understanding of what is likely to become a prototype galaxy for studying the starburst to quasar transition phase and AGN feedback.</prp:abstract>
